    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-24T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-24T08:00:00-05:00" n="620"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d620">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 <gloss target="#t_EW1"
                    >EW</gloss>/6–2445: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 620<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Representative on the Allied Commission on
                        Reparations</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PEW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Pauley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d620fn1">Sent to the Acting Secretary of State over the
                        signature of <persName corresp="#p_HK1">Harriman</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-24T16:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 24, 1945—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2250. <gloss target="#t_topsec1">Top sec</gloss> from <persName corresp="#p_PEW1"
                        >Pauley</persName> for the Secretary.</p>
                <p>I am informed that the US has in effect waived any claim to reparation (other
                    than compensation for damages to Amer property) from both <persName
                        corresp="#p_R3">Rumania</persName> and Hungary and that similar action is
                    contemplated on the part of the Allied powers in the case of Austria. However,
                        <pb facs="1077" n="943" xml:id="pg_943"/> surplus of certain commodities
                    available for export from <persName corresp="#p_R3">Rumania</persName>, Hungary
                    and Austria such as oils and agricultural products are presently being supplied
                    Amer occupation forces in Germany from the US. If these supplies could be made
                    available to such forces by reverse Lend-Lease from the Soviet Union which has
                    just announced it is expecting to receive some of these commodities from Hungary
                    and <persName corresp="#p_R3">Rumania</persName> as reparations it would both
                    greatly assist in waging war against <persName corresp="#p_J1">Japan</persName>
                    and increase the net amount of reparations which we may be able to secure from
                    Germany. I shall appreciate anything you may be able to do along these lines and
                    I shall be glad to assist here in our dealings with the Soviet Union in any way
                    which you may suggest.<note n="2" xml:id="d620fn2">The Department was informed
                        by the United States Delegation at Babelsberg on July 21 (telegram <hi
                            rend="smallcaps">Victoby</hi> 181, file No. 740.00119 <gloss
                            target="#t_EW1">EW</gloss>/7–2145) that, in view of a United States
                        proposal made to the Berlin Conference (see <ref
                            target="frus1945Berlinv02#d1320">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>,
                            document No. 1320</ref>), no further action on <persName
                            corresp="#p_PEW1">Pauley</persName>’s telegram No. 2250 was necessary,
                        and that the reverse lend-lease issue had been dropped.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
